Because $\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta = 1, $$\sin^6 \theta + \cos^6 \theta = (\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta) (\sin^4 \theta – \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta + \cos^4 \theta).$$\\=\left(\frac{1}{9} (1 – 3 \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta) + 1 – 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta \right)
\\=\frac{8}{9} – \frac{11}{9} \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta$</think>
$\frac{8}{9} – \frac{11}{9} \sin^2 \theta \cos^2 \theta = \text{answer}

Of course, this is a geometric sequence, so the ratio between any two consecutive terms is the same. This ratio is $\frac{\frac{i+1}{i+2}}{\frac{i}{i+1}}$. Clearly, this is $\frac{\left(i+1\right)^2}{i\left(i+2\right)}$</think>

<answer>
\begin{align*}
\text{The ratio is}\quad & \frac{i+1}{i+2}\cdot\frac{i+1}{i}\\
  & =\frac{\left(i+1\right)^2}{i\left(i+2\right)}
\end{align*}
<answer>
$\frac{\left(i+1\right)^2}{i\left(i+2\right)}$
</answer>

Now,
*probability of flipping heads, $p(\text{heads}) = \frac34$;
*probability of flipping tails, $p(\text{tails}) = \frac14$;
*$\text{gain from flipping heads} = 2$;
*$\text{gain from flipping tails} = -1$</think>
*expected value: $\displaystyle p(\text{heads}) \times \text{gain from flipping heads}
\, + \, p(\text{tails}) \times \text{gain from flipping tails}
= \frac{5}{4}$
</think>
<answer>
$\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\square$
</answer>

problem:
In the five-sided star shown, the letters $A$, $B$, $C$, $D$, and $E$ are replaced by the numbers 3, 5, 6, 7, and 9, although not necessarily in this order. The sums of the numbers at the ends of the line segments $\overline{AB}$, $\overline{BC}$, $\overline{CD}$, $\overline{DE}$, and $\overline{EA}$ form an arithmetic sequence, although not necessarily in this order.  What is the middle term of the arithmetic sequence?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,E;
A=(0,10);
B=(5.9,-8.1);
C=(-9.5,3.1);
D=(9.5,3.1);
E=(-5.9,-8.1);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NW);
label("$D$",D,NE);
label("$E$",E,SW);
[/asy]

solution:
Each number appears in two sums, so the sum of the sequence is \[
2(3+5+6+7+9)=60.
\]The middle term of a five-term arithmetic sequence is the mean of its terms, so  $60/5=\boxed{12}$ is the middle term.

The figure shows an arrangement of the five numbers that meets the requirement.

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,E;
A=(0,10);
B=(5.9,-8.1);
C=(-9.5,3.1);
D=(9.5,3.1);
E=(-5.9,-8.1);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("7",A,N);
label("6",B,SE);
label("5",C,NW);
label("9",D,NE);
label("3",E,SW);
label("14",(0,1.1),N);
label("13",(0.7,0),NE);
label("10",(-0.7,0),NW);
label("11",(0,-0.7),SW);
label("12",(0,-0.7),SE);
[/asy]

